{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c94d752-2d8b-4e63-9824-483fae618dea","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle methods**. Create a custom `Window` subclass and override the relevant methods:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    // ≈ OnStart\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnDeactivated() // ≈ OnSleep\n    {\n        base.OnDeactivated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()     // ≈ OnResume\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class, return it from `CreateWindow`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n```\n\n**Quick mapping:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnDeactivated()` / `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `OnActivated()` |\n\nFor platform-specific hooks, you can also use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36bd5029-c5a5-42f0-9dfa-185a316e9a83","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`. But more directly, the `Window` class has overridable methods or you can subscribe to events on the `Window`.\n\nActually, let me be more precise:\n\n1. \n\nIn MAUI, the `Window` class provides virtual methods like `OnCreated()`, `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, and `OnDestroying()` that you can override for lifecycle handling. The `Application` class no longer has the `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` methods from Xamarin.Forms — those have been replaced by the Window-level lifecycle events.\n\nTo hook into these events, I can either create a custom `Window` subclass and override the methods directly, or use the `CreateWindow` override in my `App` class. I could also leverage `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` for platform-specific handling if needed.","outputTokens":835},"id":"2b416296-d69c-49ef-9952-fe745b40bd08","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:43:36.337Z","parentId":"92a77cb4-dd05-4f57-babb-5bba82d6b5dc"}
